# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: george-westinghouse
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:george-westinghouse/11-stanwix-street] 11 Stanwix Street was completed on November 24, 1969, with twenty-three floors.
[src:george-westinghouse/11-stanwix-street] This tower rises 355 feet (108 meters) above Downtown Pittsburgh and is located near the Monongahela River.
[src:george-westinghouse/11-stanwix-street] A ten-story building that once served as the city's main post was previously located on this site.
[src:george-westinghouse/11-stanwix-street] During this building's early years, one of the tenants was Federal Home Loan Bank (FHLB) of Pittsburgh, which occupied the third and fourth floors.
[src:george-westinghouse/11-stanwix-street] FHLB later moved to the National Steel Building on Stanwix Street, finally making its permanent home in the Porter Building on Grant Street, now renamed for FHLB.
[src:george-westinghouse/11-stanwix-street] As of June 2009, the building tenants were IBM, the Allegheny Conference on Community Development, Carmeuse North America, the advertising firm Brunner, and the local headquarters of KeyCorp.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] The **A2W reactor** is a naval nuclear reactor used by the United States Navy to provide electricity generation and propulsion on warships.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] This nuclear reactor was used in the world's first nuclear-powered aircraft carrier, the USS *Enterprise* (CVN-65).
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] The four propulsion plants on *Enterprise* each contained two reactors, numbered according to the shaft they powered, 1A-1B, 2A-2B, 3A-3B, and 4A-4B.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] Each propulsion plant was capable of operating on one reactor plant through most of the power range required to propel the ship at speeds in excess of 33 knots (60 km/h).
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] Both reactors would have been on-line to simultaneously provide maximum ship speed and plane launching capability.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] The reactors are pressurized water reactors fueled by highly enriched uranium-235.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] Light water is used as both neutron-moderator and reactor coolant.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] Hafnium Control rods are used to control the operation of the reactor.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] Extracting the rods to a calculated height allows the reactor to reach criticality, the point at which the nuclear fission reactions reach a self-sustaining level.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] Thereafter, steam flow (from the steam generators) regulates reactor power as explained below.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] The control rods are "shimmed" in or out to regulate average coolant temperature or lowered to the bottom of the reactor vessel to shut the reactor down — either done in a slow controlled manner or dropped rapidly during what is called a SCRAM to immediately shut the reactor down in an emergency.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] Much of the reactor power control during steady-state operation comes as a result of the coolant water's negative temperature coefficient.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] The power of the reactor is determined by the instantaneous rate of fission events that take place in the fuel.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] As the water heats up, it expands and becomes less dense, which provides fewer molecules per volume to moderate the neutrons, hence fewer neutrons are slowed to the required thermal energies to sustain thermal fission.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] Conversely, when the coolant water temperature decreases, its density increases and a greater number of neutrons reach the required thermal energy, increasing the number of fissions per unit of time, creating more heat.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] This has the effect of allowing "steam demand" to control reactor power, requiring little intervention by the Reactor Operator for changes in the power demanded by the ship's operations.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] The hot water from the reactors is sent, via large pipes, into heat exchangers called steam generators.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] There the heat from the pressurized, superheated reactor coolant water is transferred, through tube walls, to water being fed into the steam generators from a separate feed system.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] Once the reactor coolant water has given off its heat in the steam generators, it is returned, via large electric pumps (four per reactor), to the reactors to repeat the cycle.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] Saturated steam is channeled from each steam generator to a common header, where the steam is then sent to the main engine, electrical generators, aircraft catapult system, and various auxiliaries.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] There are two main propulsion turbines, one high pressure turbine and one low pressure turbine, with a moisture separator in place between the two.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] The Low Pressure main propulsion turbine is double-ended, whereby the steam enters at the center and divides into two streams as it enters the actual turbine wheels, expanding and giving up its energy as it does so, causing the turbine to spin at high speed.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] The main shaft enters a reduction gear in which the high rotational velocity of the turbine shaft is stepped down to a usable turn rate for propelling the ship.
[src:george-westinghouse/a2w-reactor] The expended steam from the main engine and other auxiliaries enters condensers to be cooled into liquid water and recycled to the feed system.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to a match with Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:george-westinghouse/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The Adams power plant followed an 1886 plan by engineer Thomas Evershed to tap the power of Niagara Falls, which involved a "hydraulic canal" and a 7,500 feet (2,300 m) brick-lined tunnel, when the Niagara Falls Power Company was formed.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The Cataract Construction Company, a new company formed to exploit the opportunity, led by president Edward Dean Adams, first formed the International Niagara Commission in 1890 to come up with a plan for harnessing the Falls.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The Commission favored electricity, but could not recommend a solution to Cataract.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] In 1892, George Forbes was hired as a technical consultant and in May 1893 he convinced the company to build a hydroelectric system based on polyphase alternating current.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] Westinghouse Electric was subcontracted to build 5,000 horsepower (3,700 kW) 25 Hz AC generators, based on the work of Nikola Tesla and Benjamin G.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] Morris Company of Philadelphia built the turbines based on the design of the Swiss company Faesch and Piccard.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The power plant went into operation on August 25, 1895.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The transformer house building was designed by the architectural firm of McKim, Mead, and White.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] Locally quarried limestone was used in its construction.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The transformer house was next to the power houses, which "built on the upper river, above deep excavations housing twenty-one generating units.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] Tailwater from the generators passed into a 7000-ft tailrace tunnel, which conveyed the water beneath the city to the lower river, near the present-day site of the Rainbow Bridge.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The 18-ft by 21-ft tunnel required over 3 years to build, used more than 16 million bricks in a four-course lining.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] 1, as it was then called, would eventually generate 50,000 horsepower (37 MW) of electricity.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] There were 10 generator rated 5,000 horsepower (3.7 MW) of the outside revolving field, vertical shaft type.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The generators were separated into two banks of five generators each with independent switchboards.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The output was at 2,000 volts to serve in and around Niagara Falls.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] There were transformers to step up the voltage to 10,000 volts to serve the medium distance around Niagara Falls areas.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The voltage was also stepped up to 20,000 to serve the longer distance for Buffalo, Lockport, and Tonawanda.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The station was the model for a second similar station built in 1904.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The entire plant was officially named after Edward Dean Adams in 1927.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The original Westinghouse generators remained in operation until the plant closed in 1961, having been replaced by the Robert Moses Niagara Power Plant and the Lewiston Pump-Generating Plant.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The Power Plant's main arch is found on Goat Island as the Power Portal.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] The building was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1975 and was designated a National Historic Landmark in 1983 and an IEEE Milestone in 1990.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] It is located off 15th St., just south of Buffalo Avenue.
[src:george-westinghouse/adams-power-plant] It is a major contributing feature to the Niagara Falls National Heritage Area.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] Bovik received a Primetime Emmy Award in 2015 for his development of perception-based video quality measurement tools that are now standards in television production.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] Al Bovik was educated at the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign (PhD 1984).
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] He has made numerous fundamental contributions to the fields of digital photography, digital television, digital image processing, digital video processing, digital cinema, and computational visual perception.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] He is particularly well known for his work on low-level vision, natural scene modeling, image quality, and video quality.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] He has published more than 1000 technical articles, books, and patents in these areas.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] Overall, his work has been cited in the scientific and engineering literature more than 200,000 times according to Google Scholar.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] He is one of the most highly cited engineers in the world according to the Web of Science.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] Bovik is an elected member of the United States National Academy of Engineering (NAE), an elected Foreign Fellow of the Indian National Academy of Engineering (INAE), an elected Fellow of the U.S.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] National Academy of Inventors, and an elected foreign member of Academia Europaea (2023).
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] He is also a Life Fellow of the IEEE, a Fellow of Optica and of the Society of Photo-Optical and Instrumentation Engineers (SPIE), an Honorary Fellow of the Royal Photographic Society (HonFRPS) and an Honorary Member of the Society for Imaging Science and Technology (IS&T).
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] He is a voting member of the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences (Television Academy) and was named an inaugural member of its Science and Technology Peer Group.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] He was named a Distinguished Alumnus of the University of Illinois at Urbana–Champaign in 2008.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] His high-dynamic range (HDR) add-on model HDRMAX, which improves the quality prediction performance of leading models is marketed and used worldwide.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] He was the founder and First General Chair of the IEEE International Conference on Image Processing (ICIP).
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] He also co-founded (with David Munson, Jr.) the IEEE Transactions on Image Processing and was its longest-serving Editor-in-Chief, with a tenure of six years.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] Bovik's academic legacy includes serving as the supervising professor of more than 70 PhD graduates, more than 50 master's degree recipients, and more than two dozen post-doctoral researchers.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] His award-winning online courseware is used internationally: SIVA – Courseware for Signal, Image, Video and Audio Processing.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] This online courseware offers online curricula for digital image and video processing and digital signal processing.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] SIVA includes hundreds of signal, image and video processing demonstrations delivering live, interactive audio-visual experiences of signal and image processing algorithms.
[src:george-westinghouse/alan-bovik] Bovik has received a number of major international awards.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:george-westinghouse/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:george-westinghouse/alex-davison-bailey] Bailey was born in what is now Salem Lakes, Wisconsin, son of Eugene M.
[src:george-westinghouse/alex-davison-bailey] He obtained his BSc in Mechanical Engineering in 1903 from the Lewis Institute in Chicago, now Illinois Institute of Technology.
[src:george-westinghouse/alex-davison-bailey] Before his graduation Bailey had started his career as draftsman at the U.S Wind Engine and Pump Company in Batavia, Illinois, and had been trouble man at the Evanston Heating Co. in Evanston, Illinois.
[src:george-westinghouse/alex-davison-bailey] After his graduation Bailey started his lifelong career at the Chicago Edison Co., soon to be Commonwealth Edison.
[src:george-westinghouse/alex-davison-bailey] From 1903 to 1905 he started as draftsman, from 1906 to 1916 he was assistant chief engineer at Fisk Street Station, and another chief engineer.
[src:george-westinghouse/alex-davison-bailey] From 1921 to 1932 he was superintendent of generating stations of the company, and in 1933 appointed assistant chief operating engineer.
[src:george-westinghouse/alex-davison-bailey] From 1936 to 1942 he was chief operating engineer and manager of the Super Power department.
[src:george-westinghouse/alex-davison-bailey] The last years ten years at the company he was vice-president in charge of operations and engineering.
[src:george-westinghouse/alex-davison-bailey] He retired on February 1, 1952 after 48 years of service.
[src:george-westinghouse/alex-davison-bailey] In 1942 Bailey had been awarded the Honorary Doctor of Science by the Northwestern University.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] His invention of a train braking system using compressed air revolutionized the railroad industry around the world.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He founded the Westinghouse Air Brake Company in 1869.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He and his engineers also developed track-switching and signaling systems, which led to the founding of the company Union Switch & Signal in 1881.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In the early 1880s, he developed inventions for the safe production, transmission, and use of natural gas.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] This sparked the creation of a whole new energy industry.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] During this same period, Westinghouse recognized the potential of using alternating current (AC) for electric power distribution.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1886, he founded the Westinghouse Electric Corporation.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse's electric business directly competed with Thomas Edison's, who was promoting direct current (DC) electricity.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse Electric won the contract to showcase its AC system to illuminate the "White City" at the 1893 Columbian Exposition in Chicago.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The company went on to install the world's first large-scale, AC power generation plant at Niagara Falls, New York, which opened in August 1895.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Ironically, among many other honors, Westinghouse received the 1911 Edison Medal of the American Institute of Electrical Engineers "for meritorious achievement in connection with the development of the alternating current system".
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] George Westinghouse was born in 1846 in the village of Central Bridge, New York (see George Westinghouse Jr.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Birthplace and Boyhood Home), the son of Emeline (Vedder) and George Westinghouse Sr., a farmer and machine shop owner.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The Westinghouse ancestors came from Westphalia in Germany, moving first to England and eventually emigrating to the US.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The family name had been anglicized from Wistinghausen.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] From his youth, Westinghouse displayed a talent for machinery and business.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He was encouraged by his father and was assigned tasks in the Westinghouse Company workshop.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The company produced farm equipment such as the Westinghouse Farm Engine.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] At the outbreak of the Civil War in April 1861, the then 14-year-old attempted to run away from home to enlist, but was stopped by his father.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In June 1863 his parents allowed him to enlist, first in the 12th Regiment of the New York National Guard and then in the 16th Regiment of the New York Cavalry.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He earned a promotion to the rank of corporal before being honorably discharged in November 1863.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He served as an Acting Third Assistant Engineer on the gunboat USS *Muscoota* and then on the ship USS *Stars and Stripes* through the end of the war.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] These ships were used to blockade Southern port cities.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] After his discharge in August 1865, Westinghouse returned to his family and enrolled at Union College in Schenectady, but he quickly lost interest and dropped out during his first term.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He further developed his skills in his father's company shop.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse was just 19 when he received his first patent for a rotary steam engine.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] At age 21, he invented a car replacer, a device used to guide derailed railroad cars back onto the tracks, and a reversible "frog", a rail junction piece used to switch trains between different tracks.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1868, Westinghouse moved with his wife to Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, to access better and less expensive steel for the manufacture of his railroad frogs, and there he began to develop his recently invented railroad air brake concept.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] During his travels, Westinghouse had witnessed the aftermath of a collision where engineers on two trains, approaching each other on the same track, had seen each other but were unable to stop their trains in time due to the existing brake systems.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] At that time, brakemen had to run along catwalks on the top of the cars, manually applying the brakes.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Coordinating that process was tricky and dangerous.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] It also meant trains could not exceed ten cars in length, and thousands of brakemen died or were maimed each year.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1869, at age 23, Westinghouse first publicly demonstrated his revolutionary new railroad braking system in Pittsburgh.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] It stopped trains using a compressed air system.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] His first braking system used an air compressor and an air reservoir in the locomotive, with a single compressed air pipe running the length of the train and with flexible connections between cars.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] That line controlled the brakes, allowing the engineer to apply and release the brakes simultaneously on all cars.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] A charter for what would eventually become the Westinghouse Air Brake Company was filed in July of that year.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Although the system was successful, as demonstrated when it prevented a serious mishap in front of assembled witnesses, it was hardly fail-safe.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Any rupture or disconnection in the air line left the train without brakes.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Over the next two years, Westinghouse and his engineers addressed the problem by inverting the process, designing valves so that constant pressure in the lines kept the brakes disengaged.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] An air reservoir was also placed on each car.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] With the improved design, any interruption or break in the line automatically caused the train to stop.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] During the next decade, building on his earliest inventions, Westinghouse expanded his interest to railway signaling and track-switching systems.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Previously, signaling relied on oil lamps and track switching was performed manually.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse's designs changed all that.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In May 1881, Westinghouse founded the Union Switch and Signal Company to manufacture, market, install, and maintain these innovative control systems, which were eventually adopted by railroads around the world.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] By 1883, Westinghouse had become interested in natural gas.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Gas had recently been discovered in nearby Murrysville, Pennsylvania, and it attracted a lot of attention, in part because of a spectacular flaming blowout of the Haymaker Well in 1878.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] After visiting the well and recognizing its commercial potential, he undertook drilling for gas on his estate Solitude (today's Westinghouse Park) in Pittsburgh.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Early in the morning of May 21, 1884, the drilling crew struck a pocket of gas at a depth of 1500 feet, and the resulting blast of dirt and water blew the top off the derrick.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] It took Westinghouse a week to devise a method to cap the flow of gas.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He was encouraged to develop a system to deliver gas to heat and light area homes and businesses.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Eventually, several natural gas derricks towered above his estate's Victorian-era gardens.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In modern times there is no above-ground trace left of these derricks.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] That year, Westinghouse acquired a dormant utility charter for "The Philadelphia Company", and over the next three years, he developed devices and secured more than 30 patents for this technology.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He used the Philadelphia Company to develop gas wells and to promote gas usage both for commercial and residential purposes.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] By 1886, the Philadelphia Company owned 58 wells and 184 miles of distribution piping in the Pittsburgh area, and by 1887, it served over 12,000 private homes and 582 industrial customers throughout the state.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1889, as his involvement with the generation and distribution of electricity was surging, Westinghouse resigned as president of the Philadelphia Company, but he remained on its board.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Growth in the natural gas business slowed in the 1890s, hindered by supply problems and ongoing safety concerns related to gas distribution in homes and businesses.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] However, the Philadelphia Company continued to grow, spawning enterprises such as Equitable Gas and Duquesne Light.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In the early 1880s, Westinghouse's interest in railroad switching and natural gas distribution led him to become involved in the then-new field of electrical power distribution.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Electric lighting of streets using arc lighting was already a growing business with many companies building systems powered by either locally generated direct current (DC) or alternating current (AC).
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] At the same time, Thomas Edison was launching the first DC electric utility designed to light homes and businesses with his patented incandescent bulb.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1884, Westinghouse began developing his own DC domestic lighting system and hired physicist William Stanley to help work on it.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1885, Westinghouse became aware of the concept of an electrical transformer introduced by Frenchman Lucien Gaulard and Englishman John Gibbs.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse was alerted by Guido Pantaleoni, an Italian engineer in his employ, to the already-patented Gaulard-Gibbs transformer design, and to an already deployed system capable of transmitting electricity for many miles near London, Turin, and Rome.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] They had found that AC electricity could be "stepped up" in voltage by a transformer for transmission and then "stepped down" by another transformer for lower voltage consumer use.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] This innovation made it possible for large centralized power plants to generate electricity and supply it over long distances to both cities and places with more dispersed populations.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] This was a huge advantage over the low voltage DC systems being marketed by Edison’s electric utility, which limited generating stations to a transmission range of about a mile due to losses caused by the low voltages and high currents used.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse recognized AC's potential to achieve greater economies of scale as a way to create a truly competitive electrical system, rather than simply piecing together a barely competitive DC lighting system just different enough to get around Edison’s patents.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1885, Westinghouse imported several Gaulard–Gibbs transformers and a Siemens AC generator to begin experimenting with AC networks in Pittsburgh.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Stanley, assisted by engineers Albert Schmid and Oliver B.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Shallenberger, dramatically improved the Gaulard–Gibbs transformer design, creating the first practical and manufacturable transformer.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1886, with Westinghouse's backing, Stanley installed the first multiple-voltage AC power system in Great Barrington, Massachusetts.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The demonstration lighting system was driven by a hydroelectric generator that produced 500 volts AC, which was then stepped down to 100 volts to light incandescent bulbs in homes and businesses.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] That same year, Westinghouse founded the "Westinghouse Electric & Manufacturing Company"; in 1889 he renamed it the "Westinghouse Electric Corporation".
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The Westinghouse company installed thirty more AC-lighting systems within a year, and by the end of 1887 it had 68 alternating current power stations compared to 121 DC-based stations Edison had installed over seven years.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] This competition with Edison led, in the late 1880s, to what became known as the "war of currents".
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Thomas Edison and his company joined and promoted a spreading public perception that the high voltages used in AC distribution were unsafe and deadly.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Edison even suggested that a Westinghouse AC generator should be used in the State of New York's new electric chair.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse also had to deal with another AC rival, the Thomson-Houston Electric Company, which had constructed 22 power stations by the end of 1887 and by 1889 it had acquired another competitor, the Brush Electric Company.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Thomson-Houston was expanding its business while trying to avoid patent conflicts with Westinghouse, arranging deals such as agreements over lighting company territory, paying royalties to use the Stanley transformer patent, and allowing Westinghouse to use its Sawyer–Man incandescent bulb patent.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1890, the Edison company, in collusion with Thomson-Houston, arranged for the first electric chair to be powered with a Westinghouse AC generator.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse tried to block this move by hiring the best lawyer of the day to (unsuccessfully) defend William Kemmler, the first man scheduled to die in the chair.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The War of Currents ended in 1892 when financier J.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Morgan forced Edison General Electric to switch to AC power and then pushed Edison out of the company he had founded.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Edison General Electric company was merged with the Thomson-Houston Electric Company to form General Electric, a conglomerate controlled by the board of Thomson-Houston.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The acquisition of a feasible AC motor gave Westinghouse a key patented element for his system, but the financial strain of buying up patents and hiring the engineers needed to build it meant that the development of Tesla's motor had to be put on hold for a while.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1891, Westinghouse's company was in trouble.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The near collapse of Barings Bank in London triggered the financial panic of 1890, causing investors to call in their loans.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The sudden cash shortage forced the company to refinance its debts.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The new lead lenders demanded that Westinghouse cut back on what looked to them like his excessive spending on the acquisition of other companies, research, and patents.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Also in 1891, Westinghouse built a hydroelectric AC power plant, the Ames Hydroelectric Generating Plant near Ophir, Colorado which supplied AC power to the Gold King Mine 3.5 miles away.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] This was the first successful demonstration of long-distance transmission of industrial-grade alternating current power and utilized two 100 hp Westinghouse alternators, one working as a generator producing 3,000-volt, 133-Hertz, single-phase AC, and the other used as an AC motor.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In May 1892, Westinghouse Electric won the bid to power and illuminate the 1893 World's Columbian Exposition in Chicago with alternating current, substantially underbidding General Electric to get the contract.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] To meet the contract's demands, he had to quickly develop a new type of incandescent lightbulb based on the Sawyer–Man patent he had obtained, ensuring it did not infringe on the Edison patent design.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] By the beginning of 1893, Westinghouse engineer Benjamin Lamme had made great progress in developing an efficient version of Tesla's induction motor.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In that work he was aided by his sister and fellow Westinghouse engineer Bertha Lamme Feicht.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse Electric started branding their complete polyphase AC system as the "Tesla Polyphase System", announcing Tesla's patents gave them patent priority over other AC systems and stating their intention to sue any patent infringers.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] This World's Fair devoted a building to electrical exhibits.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] It was a key event in the history of AC power, as Westinghouse demonstrated the safety, reliability, and efficiency of a fully integrated alternating current system to the American public.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse's demonstration of their ability to build a complete AC system at the Columbian Exposition was instrumental in the company getting the contract for building a two-phase AC generating system, the Adams Power Plant, at Niagara Falls, NY, in 1895.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The company was subcontracted to build ten 5,000 horsepower (3,700 kW) 25 Hz AC generators at this plant.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse's Niagara Power Station No.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] 1, as it was then called, remained in operation in the Niagara transformer house until the plant closed in 1961.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] At the same time, a contract to build the three-phase AC distribution system the project needed was awarded to General Electric.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The early to mid-1890s saw General Electric, backed by financier J.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Morgan, engaged in costly takeover attempts and patent battles with Westinghouse Electric.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The competition was so costly that in 1896 a patent-sharing agreement was signed between the two companies.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The agreement stayed in effect until 1911.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] That facility opened in 1905 in Niagara Falls, Ontario.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Despite continuing success in his other businesses, Westinghouse's main interest shifted to electric power generation.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] At the outset, the available generating sources were hydro turbines where falling water was available, and reciprocating steam engines where it was not.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse felt that existing reciprocating steam engines were clumsy and inefficient, and he wanted to develop rotating engines that would be more elegant.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] His first patent had been for a rotary steam engine, but it proved impractical at the time.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1884, the British engineer Charles Algernon Parsons at Clarke, Chapman and Co began experimenting with steam turbines and generators, producing a 10-horsepower (7.5 kW) turbo-generator.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1895, Westinghouse bought rights to the Parsons turbine, and his engineers improved its technology and increased its scale.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1898, Westinghouse demonstrated a 300-kilowatt generating unit, replacing reciprocating engines in his air-brake factory.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The next year, he installed a 1.5-MW 1200 rpm unit for the Hartford Electric Light Company.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse also developed steam turbines for maritime propulsion.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The basic problem was that large turbines ran most efficiently at around 3000 rpm, while an efficient propeller operated only at about 100 rpm.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] This required reduction gearing, but designing reduction gearing that could operate at both high rpm and at high power was difficult, since any slight misalignment would shake the powertrain to pieces.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse and his engineers invented an automatic self-alignment system that finally made turbine power practical for large vessels.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1889, Westinghouse purchased several mining claims in the Patagonia Mountains of southeastern Arizona and formed the Duquesne Mining & Reduction Company.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He hoped to invent a better way to mine and extract copper from "lean" ores that were not particularly rich in the metal.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Success is this venture would have helped him compete in the electrical businesses that used much copper.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He was unsuccessful in this project: no new copper reduction process was found and the mine was not profitable.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He had founded the town of Duquesne to use as his company headquarters; it is now a ghost town.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Duquesne grew to over 1,000 residents and the mine reached its peak production in the mid-1910s.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse also began to work on heat pumps that could provide heating and cooling.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] When Westinghouse claimed he was after a perpetual motion machine, the British physicist William Thomson (Lord Kelvin), one of his many correspondents, told him that such a machine would violate the laws of thermodynamics.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse replied that while it might be the case, it made no difference.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] If he couldn't build a perpetual motion machine, he would still have a heat pump system that he could patent and sell.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] After the broader introduction of the automobile, Westinghouse invented a compressed air shock absorber for their suspension systems.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The shock absorber was among the last of the 360 patents he received, and it was awarded posthumously, two years after his death.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse was the first industrial employer in the United States to give workers a five-and-a half day work week, starting in June 1881.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Saturdays were made half holidays to promote community involvement and personal development.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse had observed the practice while visiting England.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The planned community of Wilmerding, Pennsylvania was home to many Westinghouse employees, and it was also the headquarters of several companies, particularly Westinghouse Air Brake.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse Electric and Manufacturing was located a mile further down the Turtle Creek valley east of Pittsburgh.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The worker houses were outfitted with running water, electricity, gas, and often space for small gardens.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Homeownership was facilitated through periodic salary deductions.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] There was a pension and an insurance system.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Factories were well-lit, ventilated, and were outfitted with medical facilities and personnel for treating injuries.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] All these accommodations, at Westinghouse's expense, were considered highly innovative at the time, especially in contrast to the conditions endured by workers in the nearby steel mills.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse was broadly admired by his workers.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Privately, they referred to him as "the Old Man".
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] An indication of his progressive attitude was that when Westinghouse engineers invented things, they were allowed to keep their names on the patents, though assigning rights to use them to the company.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse viewed this as part of the dignity of man and part of his intellectual property.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse, unlike Edison, did not put his name on all company patents as co-inventor.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse was not in favor of labor unionization.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He did not reject workers who belonged to a union, but he did not like collective bargaining arrangements where his workers might strike for issues not related to conditions at his own factories.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] There was only one strike at any Westinghouse company while he was in charge.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] It was a 1903 action at Westinghouse Machine Company, which was rushing to illuminate the 1904 St.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse responded by immediately hiring replacements for those employees who walked out.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Despite that action, American labor and union organizer Samuel Gompers is reputed to have said "If all employers of men treated their employees with the same consideration he does, the American Federation of Labor would have to go out of existence".
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] A series of short movies showing conditions in and around Westinghouse factories was made in 1904 and exhibited at the St.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1867, Westinghouse met Marguerite Erskine Walker on a train, and they married in August of that year.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] They were married for 47 years, and had one son, George Westinghouse III, who in turn had six children.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] From 1871, George and Marguerite Westinghouse maintained a large home in Pittsburgh called Solitude, building up from an existing house on land purchased by George in 1871.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] They were part of a social class of very rich local industrialists and money managers including neighbors and associates Henry Clay Frick, Henry J.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Heinz, William Thaw, Andrew Mellon, and Richard Beatty Mellon, and the brothers Andrew Carnegie and Thomas Carnegie.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Their guests included Nikola Tesla, Lord Kelvin, and congressman (and future president) William McKinley.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] By 1893, they had constructed Erskine Park in Lenox, Massachusetts, which they used as a summer home, in part as a respite from the gritty industrial environment of Pittsburgh.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] It was named for the family of Marguerite's grandparents.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1898, the Westinghouses leased and then in 1901 purchased the Blaine House mansion in Washington D.C.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Marguerite Westinghouse was reputed to host frequent and lavish entertainments there.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1918, their former Pittsburgh home, Solitude, was razed and the land given to the City of Pittsburgh to establish Westinghouse Park.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] The house in Erskine Park was sold by the family in 1917 and subsequently demolished.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] In 1894, the Grand Army of the Republic, a fraternal organization of Union Civil War veterans, held a week-long convention in Pittsburgh.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] George Westinghouse, being a veteran himself, hosted an evening of dinner and entertainment for more than 5,000 attendees at the newly constructed, but not yet active main buildings of the Westinghouse Electric and Manufacturing Company in East Pittsburgh.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He took on the expenses of the necessary building preparations and all the expenses of transporting people to and from the site by rail.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] George Westinghouse remained a captain of American industry until 1907 when the financial panic of 1907 led to his resignation from control of the Westinghouse Electric company.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] By 1911, he was no longer active in business, and his health was in decline.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Westinghouse died on March 12, 1914, in New York City at age 67.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] He was initially interred in Woodlawn Cemetery, Bronx, NY then removed on December 14, 1915.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] As a Civil War veteran, he was buried in Arlington National Cemetery, along with his wife Marguerite, who survived him by three months.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] She had also been initially interred in Woodlawn but removed and reinterred at the same time as George.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] George Westinghouse was deeply appreciated by his colleagues and employees.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] List of Honors and Awards adapted from Ref.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] During his lifetime, the companies of George Westinghouse were widely distributed in the Pittsburgh region.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Below is a sampling of U.S. patents for inventions by George Westinghouse.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Many of the same inventions were also patented in foreign countries, including Austria, Australia, Canada, Denmark, France, Germany, Great Britain, Spain, and Switzerland.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] Many additional patents were filed in the names of his companies or various of his engineers.
[src:george-westinghouse/george-westinghouse] A full list of U.S. patents can be found in Ref.
